# DevPulse

**Automated GitHub activity tracking with AI-generated weekly team reports delivered to Slack.**

[![Java](https://img.shields.io/badge/Java-21-orange?style=flat-square&logo=openjdk)](https://openjdk.org/)
[![Spring Boot](https://img.shields.io/badge/Spring%20Boot-4.0-brightgreen?style=flat-square&logo=springboot)](https://spring.io/projects/spring-boot)
[![PostgreSQL](https://img.shields.io/badge/PostgreSQL-15-blue?style=flat-square&logo=postgresql)](https://www.postgresql.org/)
[![Docker](https://img.shields.io/badge/Docker-Containerised-2496ED?style=flat-square&logo=docker)](https://www.docker.com/)
[![CI/CD](https://img.shields.io/badge/CI%2FCD-GitHub%20Actions-black?style=flat-square&logo=githubactions)](https://github.com/features/actions)

</div>

---

## The Problem

Small dev teams have a visibility problem. GitHub Insights is too basic. Jira is too heavyweight. Nobody writes changelogs manually. Every Friday, engineering leads are left asking ‚Äî *what did we actually ship this week?*

DevPulse solves this with zero behavior change from the team. It watches your GitHub activity silently, computes meaningful metrics nightly, and delivers a human-readable AI-generated summary to your Slack channel every Monday morning. Nobody logs into a dashboard. Nobody fills out a form. It just works.

---

## How It Works

```
GitHub Activity
      ‚îÇ
      ‚ñº
[POST /api/webhooks/github]
      ‚îÇ  HMAC-SHA256 signature verification
      ‚îÇ  Idempotency check via delivery ID
      ‚ñº
  raw_events table (PostgreSQL)
      ‚îÇ
      ‚îÇ  Nightly at 2am
      ‚ñº
MetricsComputationService
      ‚îÇ  Commit counts, PR timing, contributor breakdown
      ‚îÇ  Bug fix vs feature ratio from commit messages
      ‚ñº
weekly_metrics table (PostgreSQL)
      ‚îÇ
      ‚îÇ  Every Monday at 9am
      ‚ñº
  Gemini API  ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫  AI-generated summary
      ‚îÇ
      ‚ñº
  Slack channel  ‚óÑ‚îÄ‚îÄ  Team wakes up informed
      ‚îÇ
      ‚ñº
delivery_logs table (audit trail)
```

**Two decoupled worlds:**
- **Reactive** ‚Äî webhook ingestion, responds in milliseconds, always available
- **Scheduled** ‚Äî analysis and reporting, runs on a timer, completely independent

---

## Features

- **Secure webhook ingestion** ‚Äî HMAC-SHA256 signature verification with constant-time comparison to prevent timing attacks
- **Idempotent event processing** ‚Äî duplicate webhook delivery detection via GitHub's `X-GitHub-Delivery` header
- **Nightly metrics computation** ‚Äî commit frequency, PR merge time, contributor breakdown, bug fix vs feature ratio
- **AI-generated reports** ‚Äî Gemini API transforms raw metrics into a readable Monday morning Slack message
- **Full audit trail** ‚Äî every delivery attempt logged with status, timestamp, and report preview
- **Manual trigger API** ‚Äî fire analysis or reports on demand without waiting for the scheduler
- **Atomic operations** ‚Äî `@Transactional` ensures metrics save and event marking happen together or not at all
- **Containerised** ‚Äî full stack runs with a single `docker-compose up` command

---

## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Language | Java 21 | LTS, modern records and text blocks |
| Framework | Spring Boot 4 | Industry standard Java backend |
| ORM | Spring Data JPA + Hibernate 7 | Zero SQL for standard operations |
| Database | PostgreSQL 15 | JSONB support, relational structure for time-series queries |
| AI | Gemini API | Natural language report generation from structured metrics |
| Delivery | Slack Incoming Webhooks | Zero-friction delivery to existing team channel |
| Container | Docker + docker-compose | Identical environment across dev, CI, and production |
| CI/CD | GitHub Actions | Automated build, test, and Docker image publish on every push |
| Cloud | Microsoft Azure | App Service for container hosting |

---

## System Design Decisions

**Why store raw payloads before processing?**
Event sourcing pattern ‚Äî raw GitHub JSON is stored verbatim before any analysis. If computation logic changes or has a bug, metrics can be recomputed from the original data. The source of truth is never lost.

**Why three separate tables?**
- `raw_events` ‚Äî write-heavy, source of truth, never deleted
- `weekly_metrics` ‚Äî read-heavy, derived from raw events, recomputable
- `delivery_logs` ‚Äî append-only audit trail, different access pattern entirely

**Why RestTemplate over WebClient?**
Gemini and Slack are called once per week. The complexity of reactive/async HTTP is not warranted for this access pattern. RestTemplate with explicit timeouts is the correct choice.

**Why constant-time signature comparison?**
Standard string comparison short-circuits on the first mismatched character. An attacker measuring response time can reconstruct the valid signature character by character. Constant-time comparison removes the timing signal entirely.

**What does `@Transactional` protect in metrics computation?**
Saving `WeeklyMetrics` to the database and marking raw events as processed must succeed together. If the app crashes between these two operations, events would be permanently skipped. `@Transactional` rolls both back on failure ‚Äî next run starts clean.

