## Environment Variables

| Variable | Description | Required |
|---|---|---|
| `GITHUB_WEBHOOK_SECRET` | Shared secret for HMAC signature verification | Yes |
| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | Google AI Studio API key | Yes |
| `SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL` | Slack Incoming Webhook URL | Yes |
| `SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL` | PostgreSQL JDBC URL (Docker sets this automatically) | Production |
| `SPRING_DATASOURCE_USERNAME` | Database username | Production |
| `SPRING_DATASOURCE_PASSWORD` | Database password | Production |

---

## Known Limitations and Production Gaps

| Limitation | Production Solution |
|---|---|
| In-process scheduler ‚Äî jobs don't persist across restarts | Quartz Scheduler with DB-backed job state |
| Single team, single repo | Multi-tenancy with `user_id` scoping across all tables |
| Manual webhook configuration | GitHub OAuth + programmatic webhook registration via GitHub API |
| No authentication on control endpoints | Spring Security + JWT for the metrics and trigger APIs |
| Slack URL stored in config | Slack OAuth + encrypted bot token per user |

---

## What I Would Build Next

1. **GitHub OAuth onboarding** ‚Äî users connect their GitHub account, select repos, and webhooks register automatically via the GitHub API
2. **Multi-tenancy** ‚Äî `user_id` foreign key on every table, all queries scoped to the authenticated user
3. **Real-time anomaly alerts** ‚Äî a 6-hour scheduler detecting PRs open longer than team average, contributor silence, velocity drops ‚Äî immediate Slack alerts rather than waiting for Monday
4. **Frontend dashboard** ‚Äî Next.js, three screens: connect, dashboard with charts, settings
5. **Subscription tiers** ‚Äî free (1 repo), pro (5 repos, daily digest), ultra (unlimited, all event types, anomaly detection)

